00042 /* 
00043      The 'zlib' compression library provides in-memory compression and
00044   decompression functions, including integrity checks of the uncompressed
00045   data.  This version of the library supports only one compression method
00046   (deflation) but other algorithms may be added later and will have the same
00047   stream interface.
00048 
00049      For compression the application must provide the output buffer and
00050   may optionally provide the input buffer for optimization. For decompression,
00051   the application must provide the input buffer and may optionally provide
00052   the output buffer for optimization.
00053 
00054      Compression can be done in a single step if the buffers are large
00055   enough (for example if an input file is mmap'ed), or can be done by
00056   repeated calls of the compression function.  In the latter case, the
00057   application must provide more input and/or consume the output
00058   (providing more output space) before each call.
00059 
00060      The library does not install any signal handler. It is recommended to
00061   add at least a handler for SIGSEGV when decompressing; the library checks
00062   the consistency of the input data whenever possible but may go nuts
00063   for some forms of corrupted input.
00064 */
00065

00071    typedef struct z_stream_s {
00072       Bytef *next_in;           /* next input byte */
00073       uInt avail_in;            /* number of bytes available at next_in */
00074       uLong total_in;           /* total nb of input bytes read so far */
00075 
00076       Bytef *next_out;          /* next output byte should be put there */
00077       uInt avail_out;           /* remaining free space at next_out */
00078       uLong total_out;          /* total nb of bytes output so far */
00079 
00080       char *msg;                /* last error message, NULL if no error */
00081       struct internal_state FAR *state; /* not visible by applications */
00082 
00083       alloc_func zalloc;        /* used to allocate the internal state */
00084       free_func zfree;          /* used to free the internal state */
00085       voidpf opaque;            /* private data object passed to zalloc and zfree */
00086 
00087       int data_type;            /* best guess about the data type: ascii or binary */
00088       uLong adler;              /* adler32 value of the uncompressed data */
00089       uLong reserved;           /* reserved for future use */
00090    } z_stream;

00094 /*
00095    The application must update next_in and avail_in when avail_in has
00096    dropped to zero. It must update next_out and avail_out when avail_out
00097    has dropped to zero. The application must initialize zalloc, zfree and
00098    opaque before calling the init function. All other fields are set by the
00099    compression library and must not be updated by the application.
00100 
00101    The opaque value provided by the application will be passed as the first
00102    parameter for calls of zalloc and zfree. This can be useful for custom
00103    memory management. The compression library attaches no meaning to the
00104    opaque value.
00105 
00106    zalloc must return Z_NULL if there is not enough memory for the object.
00107    On 16-bit systems, the functions zalloc and zfree must be able to allocate
00108    exactly 65536 bytes, but will not be required to allocate more than this
00109    if the symbol MAXSEG_64K is defined (see zconf.h). WARNING: On MSDOS,
00110    pointers returned by zalloc for objects of exactly 65536 bytes *must*
00111    have their offset normalized to zero. The default allocation function
00112    provided by this library ensures this (see zutil.c). To reduce memory
00113    requirements and avoid any allocation of 64K objects, at the expense of
00114    compression ratio, compile the library with -DMAX_WBITS=14 (see zconf.h).
00115 
00116    The fields total_in and total_out can be used for statistics or
00117    progress reports. After compression, total_in holds the total size of
00118    the uncompressed data and may be saved for use in the decompressor
00119    (particularly if the decompressor wants to decompress everything in
00120    a single step).
00121 */

00178 /* 
00179 extern int EXPORT deflateInit OF((z_streamp strm, int level));
00180 
00181      Initializes the internal stream state for compression. The fields
00182    zalloc, zfree and opaque must be initialized before by the caller.
00183    If zalloc and zfree are set to Z_NULL, deflateInit updates them to
00184    use default allocation functions.
00185 
00186      The compression level must be Z_DEFAULT_COMPRESSION, or between 0 and 9:
00187    1 gives best speed, 9 gives best compression, 0 gives no compression at
00188    all (the input data is simply copied a block at a time).
00189    Z_DEFAULT_COMPRESSION requests a default compromise between speed and
00190    compression (currently equivalent to level 6).
00191 
00192      deflateInit returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was not
00193    enough memory, Z_STREAM_ERROR if level is not a valid compression level,
00194    Z_VERSION_ERROR if the zlib library version (zlib_version) is incompatible
00195    with the version assumed by the caller (ZLIB_VERSION).
00196    msg is set to null if there is no error message.  deflateInit does not
00197    perform any compression: this will be done by deflate().
00198 */

00201    extern int EXPORT deflate OF((z_streamp strm, int flush));
00202 /*
00203   Performs one or both of the following actions:
00204 
00205   - Compress more input starting at next_in and update next_in and avail_in
00206     accordingly. If not all input can be processed (because there is not
00207     enough room in the output buffer), next_in and avail_in are updated and
00208     processing will resume at this point for the next call of deflate().
00209 
00210   - Provide more output starting at next_out and update next_out and avail_out
00211     accordingly. This action is forced if the parameter flush is non zero.
00212     Forcing flush frequently degrades the compression ratio, so this parameter
00213     should be set only when necessary (in interactive applications).
00214     Some output may be provided even if flush is not set.
00215 
00216   Before the call of deflate(), the application should ensure that at least
00217   one of the actions is possible, by providing more input and/or consuming
00218   more output, and updating avail_in or avail_out accordingly; avail_out
00219   should never be zero before the call. The application can consume the
00220   compressed output when it wants, for example when the output buffer is full
00221   (avail_out == 0), or after each call of deflate(). If deflate returns Z_OK
00222   and with zero avail_out, it must be called again after making room in the
00223   output buffer because there might be more output pending.
00224 
00225     If the parameter flush is set to Z_PARTIAL_FLUSH, the current compression
00226   block is terminated and flushed to the output buffer so that the
00227   decompressor can get all input data available so far. For method 9, a future
00228   variant on method 8, the current block will be flushed but not terminated.
00229   Z_SYNC_FLUSH has the same effect as partial flush except that the compressed
00230   output is byte aligned (the compressor can clear its internal bit buffer)
00231   and the current block is always terminated; this can be useful if the
00232   compressor has to be restarted from scratch after an interruption (in which
00233   case the internal state of the compressor may be lost).
00234     If flush is set to Z_FULL_FLUSH, the compression block is terminated, a
00235   special marker is output and the compression dictionary is discarded; this
00236   is useful to allow the decompressor to synchronize if one compressed block
00237   has been damaged (see inflateSync below).  Flushing degrades compression and
00238   so should be used only when necessary.  Using Z_FULL_FLUSH too often can
00239   seriously degrade the compression. If deflate returns with avail_out == 0,
00240   this function must be called again with the same value of the flush
00241   parameter and more output space (updated avail_out), until the flush is
00242   complete (deflate returns with non-zero avail_out).
00243 
00244     If the parameter flush is set to Z_FINISH, pending input is processed,
00245   pending output is flushed and deflate returns with Z_STREAM_END if there
00246   was enough output space; if deflate returns with Z_OK, this function must be
00247   called again with Z_FINISH and more output space (updated avail_out) but no
00248   more input data, until it returns with Z_STREAM_END or an error. After
00249   deflate has returned Z_STREAM_END, the only possible operations on the
00250   stream are deflateReset or deflateEnd.
00251   
00252     Z_FINISH can be used immediately after deflateInit if all the compression
00253   is to be done in a single step. In this case, avail_out must be at least
00254   0.1% larger than avail_in plus 12 bytes.  If deflate does not return
00255   Z_STREAM_END, then it must be called again as described above.
00256 
00257     deflate() may update data_type if it can make a good guess about
00258   the input data type (Z_ASCII or Z_BINARY). In doubt, the data is considered
00259   binary. This field is only for information purposes and does not affect
00260   the compression algorithm in any manner.
00261 
00262     deflate() returns Z_OK if some progress has been made (more input
00263   processed or more output produced), Z_STREAM_END if all input has been
00264   consumed and all output has been produced (only when flush is set to
00265   Z_FINISH), Z_STREAM_ERROR if the stream state was inconsistent (for example
00266   if next_in or next_out was NULL), Z_BUF_ERROR if no progress is possible.
00267 */
00268

00270    extern int EXPORT deflateEnd OF((z_streamp strm));
00271 /*
00272      All dynamically allocated data structures for this stream are freed.
00273    This function discards any unprocessed input and does not flush any
00274    pending output.
00275 
00276      deflateEnd returns Z_OK if success, Z_STREAM_ERROR if the
00277    stream state was inconsistent, Z_DATA_ERROR if the stream was freed
00278    prematurely (some input or output was discarded). In the error case,
00279    msg may be set but then points to a static string (which must not be
00280    deallocated).

00300    extern int EXPORT inflate OF((z_streamp strm, int flush));
00301 /*
00302   Performs one or both of the following actions:
00303 
00304   - Decompress more input starting at next_in and update next_in and avail_in
00305     accordingly. If not all input can be processed (because there is not
00306     enough room in the output buffer), next_in is updated and processing
00307     will resume at this point for the next call of inflate().
00308 
00309   - Provide more output starting at next_out and update next_out and avail_out
00310     accordingly.  inflate() provides as much output as possible, until there
00311     is no more input data or no more space in the output buffer (see below
00312     about the flush parameter).
00313 
00314   Before the call of inflate(), the application should ensure that at least
00315   one of the actions is possible, by providing more input and/or consuming
00316   more output, and updating the next_* and avail_* values accordingly.
00317   The application can consume the uncompressed output when it wants, for
00318   example when the output buffer is full (avail_out == 0), or after each
00319   call of inflate(). If inflate returns Z_OK and with zero avail_out, it
00320   must be called again after making room in the output buffer because there
00321   might be more output pending.
00322 
00323     If the parameter flush is set to Z_PARTIAL_FLUSH, inflate flushes as much
00324   output as possible to the output buffer. The flushing behavior of inflate is
00325   not specified for values of the flush parameter other than Z_PARTIAL_FLUSH
00326   and Z_FINISH, but the current implementation actually flushes as much output
00327   as possible anyway.
00328 
00329     inflate() should normally be called until it returns Z_STREAM_END or an
00330   error. However if all decompression is to be performed in a single step
00331   (a single call of inflate), the parameter flush should be set to
00332   Z_FINISH. In this case all pending input is processed and all pending
00333   output is flushed; avail_out must be large enough to hold all the
00334   uncompressed data. (The size of the uncompressed data may have been saved
00335   by the compressor for this purpose.) The next operation on this stream must
00336   be inflateEnd to deallocate the decompression state. The use of Z_FINISH
00337   is never required, but can be used to inform inflate that a faster routine
00338   may be used for the single inflate() call.
00339 
00340     inflate() returns Z_OK if some progress has been made (more input
00341   processed or more output produced), Z_STREAM_END if the end of the
00342   compressed data has been reached and all uncompressed output has been
00343   produced, Z_NEED_DICT if a preset dictionary is needed at this point (see
00344   inflateSetDictionary below), Z_DATA_ERROR if the input data was corrupted,
00345   Z_STREAM_ERROR if the stream structure was inconsistent (for example if
00346   next_in or next_out was NULL), Z_MEM_ERROR if there was not enough memory,
00347   Z_BUF_ERROR if no progress is possible or if there was not enough room in
00348   the output buffer when Z_FINISH is used. In the Z_DATA_ERROR case, the
00349   application may then call inflateSync to look for a good compression block.
00350   In the Z_NEED_DICT case, strm->adler is set to the Adler32 value of the
00351   dictionary chosen by the compressor.
00352 */
00353

00360 
00361      inflateEnd returns Z_OK if success, Z_STREAM_ERROR if the stream state
00362    was inconsistent. In the error case, msg may be set but then points to a

00372 /*   
00373 extern int EXPORT deflateInit2 OF((z_streamp strm,
00374                                    int  level,
00375                                    int  method,
00376                                    int  windowBits,
00377                                    int  memLevel,
00378                                    int  strategy));
00379 
00380      This is another version of deflateInit with more compression options. The
00381    fields next_in, zalloc, zfree and opaque must be initialized before by
00382    the caller.
00383 
00384      The method parameter is the compression method. It must be Z_DEFLATED in
00385    this version of the library. (Method 9 will allow a 64K history buffer and
00386    partial block flushes.)
00387 
00388      The windowBits parameter is the base two logarithm of the window size
00389    (the size of the history buffer).  It should be in the range 8..15 for this
00390    version of the library (the value 16 will be allowed for method 9). Larger
00391    values of this parameter result in better compression at the expense of
00392    memory usage. The default value is 15 if deflateInit is used instead.
00393 
00394      The memLevel parameter specifies how much memory should be allocated
00395    for the internal compression state. memLevel=1 uses minimum memory but
00396    is slow and reduces compression ratio; memLevel=9 uses maximum memory
00397    for optimal speed. The default value is 8. See zconf.h for total memory
00398    usage as a function of windowBits and memLevel.
00399 
00400      The strategy parameter is used to tune the compression algorithm. Use the
00401    value Z_DEFAULT_STRATEGY for normal data, Z_FILTERED for data produced by a
00402    filter (or predictor), or Z_HUFFMAN_ONLY to force Huffman encoding only (no
00403    string match).  Filtered data consists mostly of small values with a
00404    somewhat random distribution. In this case, the compression algorithm is
00405    tuned to compress them better. The effect of Z_FILTERED is to force more
00406    Huffman coding and less string matching; it is somewhat intermediate
00407    between Z_DEFAULT and Z_HUFFMAN_ONLY. The strategy parameter only affects
00408    the compression ratio but not the correctness of the compressed output even
00409    if it is not set appropriately.
00410 
00411      If next_in is not null, the library will use this buffer to hold also
00412    some history information; the buffer must either hold the entire input
00413    data, or have at least 1<<(windowBits+1) bytes and be writable. If next_in
00414    is null, the library will allocate its own history buffer (and leave next_in
00415    null). next_out need not be provided here but must be provided by the
00416    application for the next call of deflate().
00417 
00418      If the history buffer is provided by the application, next_in must
00419    must never be changed by the application since the compressor maintains
00420    information inside this buffer from call to call; the application
00421    must provide more input only by increasing avail_in. next_in is always
00422    reset by the library in this case.
00423 
00424       deflateInit2 returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was
00425    not enough memory, Z_STREAM_ERROR if a parameter is invalid (such as
00426    an invalid method). msg is set to null if there is no error message.
00427    deflateInit2 does not perform any compression: this will be done by
00428    deflate(). 
00429 */
00430 
00431    extern int EXPORT deflateSetDictionary OF((z_streamp strm,
00432                                               const Bytef * dictionary, uInt dictLength));
00433 /*
00434      Initializes the compression dictionary (history buffer) from the given
00435    byte sequence without producing any compressed output. This function must
00436    be called immediately after deflateInit or deflateInit2, before any call
00437    of deflate. The compressor and decompressor must use exactly the same
00438    dictionary (see inflateSetDictionary).
00439      The dictionary should consist of strings (byte sequences) that are likely
00440    to be encountered later in the data to be compressed, with the most commonly
00441    used strings preferably put towards the end of the dictionary. Using a
00442    dictionary is most useful when the data to be compressed is short and
00443    can be predicted with good accuracy; the data can then be compressed better
00444    than with the default empty dictionary. In this version of the library,
00445    only the last 32K bytes of the dictionary are used.
00446      Upon return of this function, strm->adler is set to the Adler32 value
00447    of the dictionary; the decompressor may later use this value to determine
00448    which dictionary has been used by the compressor. (The Adler32 value
00449    applies to the whole dictionary even if only a subset of the dictionary is
00450    actually used by the compressor.)
00451 
00452      deflateSetDictionary returns Z_OK if success, or Z_STREAM_ERROR if a
00453    parameter is invalid (such as NULL dictionary) or the stream state
00454    is inconsistent (for example if deflate has already been called for this
00455    stream). deflateSetDictionary does not perform any compression: this will
00456    be done by deflate(). 
00457 */
00458 
00459    extern int EXPORT deflateCopy OF((z_streamp dest, z_streamp source));
00460 /*
00461      Sets the destination stream as a complete copy of the source stream.  If
00462    the source stream is using an application-supplied history buffer, a new
00463    buffer is allocated for the destination stream.  The compressed output
00464    buffer is always application-supplied. It's the responsibility of the
00465    application to provide the correct values of next_out and avail_out for the
00466    next call of deflate.
00467 
00468      This function can be useful when several compression strategies will be
00469    tried, for example when there are several ways of pre-processing the input
00470    data with a filter. The streams that will be discarded should then be freed
00471    by calling deflateEnd.  Note that deflateCopy duplicates the internal
00472    compression state which can be quite large, so this strategy is slow and
00473    can consume lots of memory.
00474 
00475      deflateCopy returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was not
00476    enough memory, Z_STREAM_ERROR if the source stream state was inconsistent
00477    (such as zalloc being NULL). msg is left unchanged in both source and
00478    destination.
00479 */

00492    extern int EXPORT deflateParams OF((z_streamp strm, int level, int strategy));
00493 /*
00494      Dynamically update the compression level and compression strategy.
00495    This can be used to switch between compression and straight copy of
00496    the input data, or to switch to a different kind of input data requiring
00497    a different strategy. If the compression level is changed, the input
00498    available so far is compressed with the old level (and may be flushed);
00499    the new level will take effect only at the next call of deflate().
00500 
00501      Before the call of deflateParams, the stream state must be set as for
00502    a call of deflate(), since the currently available input may have to
00503    be compressed and flushed. In particular, strm->avail_out must be non-zero.
00504 
00505      deflateParams returns Z_OK if success, Z_STREAM_ERROR if the source
00506    stream state was inconsistent or if a parameter was invalid, Z_BUF_ERROR
00507    if strm->avail_out was zero.
00508 */

00510 /*   
00511 extern int EXPORT inflateInit2 OF((z_streamp strm,
00512                                    int  windowBits));
00513 
00514      This is another version of inflateInit with more compression options. The
00515    fields next_out, zalloc, zfree and opaque must be initialized before by
00516    the caller.
00517 
00518      The windowBits parameter is the base two logarithm of the maximum window
00519    size (the size of the history buffer).  It should be in the range 8..15 for
00520    this version of the library (the value 16 will be allowed soon). The
00521    default value is 15 if inflateInit is used instead. If a compressed stream
00522    with a larger window size is given as input, inflate() will return with
00523    the error code Z_DATA_ERROR instead of trying to allocate a larger window.
00524 
00525      If next_out is not null, the library will use this buffer for the history
00526    buffer; the buffer must either be large enough to hold the entire output
00527    data, or have at least 1<<windowBits bytes.  If next_out is null, the
00528    library will allocate its own buffer (and leave next_out null). next_in
00529    need not be provided here but must be provided by the application for the
00530    next call of inflate().
00531 
00532      If the history buffer is provided by the application, next_out must
00533    never be changed by the application since the decompressor maintains
00534    history information inside this buffer from call to call; the application
00535    can only reset next_out to the beginning of the history buffer when
00536    avail_out is zero and all output has been consumed.
00537 
00538       inflateInit2 returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was
00539    not enough memory, Z_STREAM_ERROR if a parameter is invalid (such as
00540    windowBits < 8). msg is set to null if there is no error message.
00541    inflateInit2 does not perform any decompression: this will be done by
00542    inflate().
00543 */
00544

00546                                               const Bytef * dictionary, uInt dictLength));
00547 /*
00548      Initializes the decompression dictionary (history buffer) from the given
00549    uncompressed byte sequence. This function must be called immediately after
00550    a call of inflate if this call returned Z_NEED_DICT. The dictionary chosen
00551    by the compressor can be determined from the Adler32 value returned by this
00552    call of inflate. The compressor and decompressor must use exactly the same

00554 
00555      inflateSetDictionary returns Z_OK if success, Z_STREAM_ERROR if a

00564 /* 
00565     Skips invalid compressed data until the special marker (see deflate()
00566   above) can be found, or until all available input is skipped. No output
00567   is provided.
00568 
00569     inflateSync returns Z_OK if the special marker has been found, Z_BUF_ERROR
00570   if no more input was provided, Z_DATA_ERROR if no marker has been found,
00571   or Z_STREAM_ERROR if the stream structure was inconsistent. In the success
00572   case, the application may save the current current value of total_in which
00573   indicates where valid compressed data was found. In the error case, the
00574   application may repeatedly call inflateSync, providing more input each time,
00575   until success or end of the input data.

00599    extern int EXPORT compress OF((Bytef * dest, uLongf * destLen,
00600                                   const Bytef * source, uLong sourceLen));
00601 /*
00602      Compresses the source buffer into the destination buffer.  sourceLen is
00603    the byte length of the source buffer. Upon entry, destLen is the total
00604    size of the destination buffer, which must be at least 0.1% larger than
00605    sourceLen plus 12 bytes. Upon exit, destLen is the actual size of the
00606    compressed buffer.
00607      This function can be used to compress a whole file at once if the
00608    input file is mmap'ed.
00609      compress returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was not
00610    enough memory, Z_BUF_ERROR if there was not enough room in the output
00611    buffer.
00612 */
00613 
00614    extern int EXPORT uncompress OF((Bytef * dest, uLongf * destLen,
00615                                     const Bytef * source, uLong sourceLen));
00616 /*
00617      Decompresses the source buffer into the destination buffer.  sourceLen is
00618    the byte length of the source buffer. Upon entry, destLen is the total
00619    size of the destination buffer, which must be large enough to hold the
00620    entire uncompressed data. (The size of the uncompressed data must have
00621    been saved previously by the compressor and transmitted to the decompressor
00622    by some mechanism outside the scope of this compression library.)
00623    Upon exit, destLen is the actual size of the compressed buffer.
00624      This function can be used to decompress a whole file at once if the
00625    input file is mmap'ed.
00626 
00627      uncompress returns Z_OK if success, Z_MEM_ERROR if there was not
00628    enough memory, Z_BUF_ERROR if there was not enough room in the output
00629    buffer, or Z_DATA_ERROR if the input data was corrupted.

00709    extern uLong EXPORT adler32 OF((uLong adler, const Bytef * buf, uInt len));
00710 
00711 /*
00712      Update a running Adler-32 checksum with the bytes buf[0..len-1] and
00713    return the updated checksum. If buf is NULL, this function returns
00714    the required initial value for the checksum.
00715    An Adler-32 checksum is almost as reliable as a CRC32 but can be computed
00716    much faster. Usage example:
00717 
00718      uLong adler = adler32(0L, Z_NULL, 0);
00719 
00720      while (read_buffer(buffer, length) != EOF) {
00721        adler = adler32(adler, buffer, length);
00722      }
00723      if (adler != original_adler) error();
00724 */
00725 
00726    extern uLong EXPORT crc32 OF((uLong crc, const Bytef * buf, uInt len));
00727 /*
00728      Update a running crc with the bytes buf[0..len-1] and return the updated
00729    crc. If buf is NULL, this function returns the required initial value
00730    for the crc. Pre- and post-conditioning (one's complement) is performed
00731    within this function so it shouldn't be done by the application.
00732    Usage example:
00733 
00734      uLong crc = crc32(0L, Z_NULL, 0);
00735 
00736      while (read_buffer(buffer, length) != EOF) {
00737        crc = crc32(crc, buffer, length);
00738      }
00739      if (crc != original_crc) error();
00740 */
